# Glossary Generator — example configuration
# Copy to ".env" (same folder as app.py) and edit. Every line is OPTIONAL.
# The real environment always wins over .env, so exported vars override these.
#
#   cp .env.example .env
#   ./run.sh                 # http://127.0.0.1:5000  (this app's default port)
#
# NOTE: this is the Glossary Generator. It is a DIFFERENT app from
# Catalog Insights / PDC-Insights (which uses port 8660). Keep their ports apart.

# ---- Web server -----------------------------------------------------------
# HOST=127.0.0.1
# PORT=5000                       # default. run.sh --port <n> also works.

# ---- Local LLM (Ollama) — optional; used for enrichment + expertise ------
# OLLAMA_URL=http://localhost:11434
# LLM_MODEL=llama3.2:3b
# LLM_TIMEOUT=30
# LLM_WORKERS=4
# LLM_BATCH=6

# ---- Scenario branding ----------------------------------------------------
# GLOSSARY_COMPANY=Copper State Credit Union

# ---- Scenario domain bundle — OFF by default -------------------------------
# The engine ships GENERIC. Simplest install for the Copper State Credit Union
# (CSCU) scenario: unzip data_sources/CSCU/cscu-domain-pack.zip into this folder
# (drops domain_pack.json + people.json - auto-loaded, no variables needed).
# Or point the variables at the pack files instead:
#   - the vocabulary (table->category map, curated terms, abbreviations), and
#   - the seed roster (CSCU people + expertise), copied into the live roster ONCE
#     on first run when it is missing/empty. Live edits and Keycloak fetches always
#     win afterwards, so the seed never overwrites a roster that already has people.
# GLOSSARY_DOMAIN_PACK=../data_sources/CSCU/domain_pack/credit_union.example.json
# GLOSSARY_PEOPLE_SEED=../data_sources/CSCU/domain_pack/credit_union.people.json

# ---- File locations (defaults sit beside app.py) --------------------------
# GLOSSARY_PEOPLE=people.json
# GLOSSARY_SETTINGS=settings.json
# GLOSSARY_CONNECTIONS=connections.json
# GLOSSARY_GLOSSARIES=glossaries.json
# GLOSSARY_DDL=/path/to/01-schema-and-data.sql
